# TypeScript Language Context

- TypeScript is the default programming language for source code.
- Prefer strict typing and explicit types at boundaries.
- Prefer `type` declarations over `interface` by default.
- Use `interface` only when it is required by a specific use case (for example declaration merging or class contract patterns).
- When an `interface` is used, it must start with the `I` prefix.
- Port contracts must also use the `I` prefix for consistency with backend rules (for example `IUserReadQueryPort`).
- Use Zod v4 as the source of truth for all domain and transport schemas.
- Derive TypeScript types from Zod schemas using `z.infer` whenever possible.
- All DTO declarations must use the `Dto` suffix.

## Typing Preference Example

```ts
// Preferred for most domain and transport shapes
type UserDto = {
	id: string;
	email: string;
	tenantIds: string[];
};

// Allowed only when interface-specific behavior is required (I prefix for non-port contracts)
interface IUserRepository {
	findById(id: string): Promise<UserDto | null>;
}

// Port contracts also use the I prefix
interface IUserRepositoryPort {
	findById(id: string): Promise<UserDto | null>;
}
```
